{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564964"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:21:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:21:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17171"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17171"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.31,0.16,0.03,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9861"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68975"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9861"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54432"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"451"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23117"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68975"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of worsening cough, haemoptysis, and right-sided chest pain. He reports losing 5 kg over the past two months without trying. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has smoked 40 cigarettes daily for 45 years. He works as a retired builder with previous asbestos exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is reduced air entry and dullness to percussion in the right upper zone. His corrected calcium is 3.2 mmol/L (2.1-2.6).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray reveals a 6 cm mass in the right upper lobe with associated collapse. CT scan confirms a central mass with invasion of the right main bronchus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lung adenocarcinoma","Small cell lung cancer","Mesothelioma","Large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of lung cancer, specifically \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The central location of the mass, presence of haemoptysis, and paraneoplastic hypercalcaemia are characteristic features. Squamous cell carcinoma typically arises in the central airways and has the strongest association with smoking among all lung cancer subtypes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cell lung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with central disease and has a strong association with smoking. However, it tends to present with more extensive disease, often with widespread metastases at diagnosis, and is more commonly associated with paraneoplastic syndromes such as SIADH rather than hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a peripheral mass and is the most common type of lung cancer in non-smokers. While it can occur in smokers, the central location and hypercalcaemia would be less typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge cell neuroendocrine carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare and aggressive form of lung cancer that can present similarly to small cell lung cancer. However, it is much less common than squamous cell carcinoma and does not typically cause hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesothelioma\u003C/strong\u003E, while associated with asbestos exposure, typically presents with pleural thickening or pleural effusion rather than a central mass. It also has a longer latency period (typically 30-50 years) from asbestos exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of heavy smoking history, central mass location, haemoptysis, and hypercalcaemia strongly supports squamous cell carcinoma as the diagnosis. Paraneoplastic hypercalcaemia occurs in up to 20% of squamous cell lung cancers due to production of parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma of the lung typically presents centrally and may cause haemoptysis, cough, and post-obstructive pneumonia.","Paraneoplastic hypercalcaemia is more common in squamous cell carcinoma than other types of lung cancer.","Smoking is the strongest risk factor for squamous cell carcinoma of the lung."],"references":["Hendriks LEL, Remon J, Faivre-Finn C, Garassino MC, Heymach JV, Kerr KM, et al. Non-small-cell lung cancer. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024 Sep 26;10(1):1\u201322."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54432"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17171"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54432"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T19:27:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T19:28:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9861"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68975"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1